data.text:
2006-07: Made one start and saw action in 25 games. …Finished fifth on the team in scoring (5.0 ppg). Reached double figures in scoring three times with a career high 19 against Lycoming College. Collected six or more rebounds nine times. Cook grabbed a season-high 10 rebounds twice against Rutgers-Camden and Lycoming. Was fourth in steals (43) and had a season high five against Brooklyn College.

2005-06: Saw action in 27 games and made one start (College of St. Elizabeth’s). …Averaged 5.4 rebounds and 5.4 points per game for Lincoln. …Grabbed 10 or more rebounds three times. …Recorded her only double-double in an 80-66 victory over Mitchell College (11 points, 10 rebounds). …Snatched a career high 13 rebounds in the win against St. Elizabeth’s. …Scored 12 points and grabbed six rebounds in 83-40 win over Green Mountain College in the Association of Division III Independents Northeast Regional tournament third place game. …Cook scored nine or more points and grabbed five or more rebounds in her final five games, averaging 9.2 points during that span. …Finished tied for second on the team in 3-pointers made with nine. …Had 10 rebounds and eight points in 79-71 win over Newport News Apprentice School. …Grabbed eight rebounds twice against Susquehanna and Delaware Valley College.

Prior to Lincoln: Cook was a two-year performer for the Jaguars, coming off the bench as a junior starting as a senior. Cook averaged 9 points per game during her senior year to help Charles H. Flowers advance to the MSSAA Class 4A semifinals. During her junior year, Cook was a valuable member of the Jaguars’ 2003-04 MSSAA Class 4A runner-ups. Cook was a solid softball player too. A three-year starter, Cook saw action at catcher, second base, third base, shortstop and in the outfield
